# Warcraft Item Guide (WIP)

___

This document is intended to act as a list of items to be used in the Warcraft 5e setting. As someone more familiar with the 3.5 edition of Dungeons and Dragons, feedback on the items created would be appreciated, to help ensure that they are balanced and ready to use in any campaigns. 

Eventually this guide will be a fully fleshed out document with many items, relics, and artifacts that are tied to the Warcraft setting and lore. But as it is a work in progress, there are some items that will be listed as mere placeholders to be updated in the future.

\pagebreakNum

# Equipment

___

This section will feature simple equipment, such as the kinds listed in the Player's Handbook. Sometimes it will be new items and sometimes it will be existing items that have an altered description or stats to better fit the setting.

For example, in Dungeons and Dragons the presumed setting is that of a medieval society with little to no technological advancements. Hence, an item like a spyglass is priced at 1,000 gold pieces to indicate that it is a hard-to-contruct rarity. Yet in Azeroth, the technological prowess of the gnomes and the metallurgic skills of the dwarves has resulted in a great many telescopes, whether in massive spy telescopes, naval spyglasses, or scopes mounted onto firearms. Thus, it is likely that a spyglass would go for much cheaper in a Warcraft-based setting.

## Idea List

### Adventuring Gear

The following items belong to the Adventuring Gear section of the PHB.

***Arcane Focus.*** Additional types: Cystallized Mana, Fel Crystal.

***Army Knife.*** [Gnomish](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Gnomish_Army_Knife)/[Goblin](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Goblin_army_knife) varieties. Can be used as one of: Back scratcher, Block and tackle, crowbar, fishing rod, hammer, firestarter, magnifying glass, mirror, five-foot pole (alternate use of fishing rod), 25 feet silk rope and a grappling hook, saw, sewing needle, three kinds of signal whistles, shovel, a 1-person tent, whetstone, a whirly thing. Also cuts things as a small knife. 4 lbs, 70 gp. Other varieties exist, including other options like thieve's tools or jumper cables.

***Beacon.*** See *flashlight*.

***Book.*** Price reduced to 10 gp, representing the increased literacy of Azeroth.

***[Buzzbox](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Buzzbox).*** Large, heavy and unwieldy methods of communication. About the size of a chest, weigs 75 lbs and costs 1,000 gp. Requires a [punch card](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Punch_card) relevant to another specific buzzbox to communicate with it. Activating or using the device requires an DC 10 Intelligence check and it needs maintenance once a day (an Intelligence/tinker's tools check). If the maintenance is not performed or if the check fails, the machine jams and needs a DC 12 tinker's tool check to repair. Range of communication is 8 miles across an open plain, about 4 miles in a 'normal' setting like a light forest, and drops down to 1-2 miles in a dense forest or city. Inclement weather can likewise cut down on the range between devices. Some gnomes have managed to chain several buzzboxes together to provide communication over long distances.

***Calculator.*** Permanent version of the gnome tinker invention, supplements/replaces the abacus. Priced at 25 gp -- basically if a gnome took the time to make the item through the crafting rules, plus a little bit more.

***Component Pouch.*** *Variant rule:* Renamed *reagent pouch*, as spells in WoW Classic use "reagents" instead of "components."

***Druidic focus.*** *New type/Variant name:* **Idol**, representing the druid-only relic type from WoW Classic.

***Firestarter.*** Permanent version of the gnome tinker invention, supplements/replaces the tinderbox. Priced at 25 gp -- basically if a gnome took the time to make the item through the crafting rules, plus a little bit more.

***Flashlight.*** Flashlights and spotlights are regular enough sights among gnome inventions that their inclusion is not out of place. Flashlights act as bullseye lanterns and "beacons" acted as hooded lanterns. Either costs 50 gp--the same price as making a light with the continual flame spell.

***Goggles.*** Provides the benefit of a magnifying glass. 10 gp.

***Holy Symbol.*** Two new types: **Totem** and **Libram**, representing the shaman and paladin-only relics from WoW Classic. Even if totem already exists in the druidic focus section...

***Hourglass.*** Price reduced to 2.5 gp.

***Ink.*** Price reduced to 1 gp.

***[Light Scope](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Light_Scope).*** Basically a laser pointer. 10 gp.

***Magnifying Glass.*** Price reduced to 10 gp.

***Mirror, Steel.*** Price reduced to 5 sp.

***Spellbook.*** Price reduced to 20 gp.

***Spyglass.*** Price reduced to 100 gp.

***[Steamsaw](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Steamsaw).*** Unknown stats.

***Timepiece.*** Permanent version of gnome tinker invention, supplements/replaces the hourglass. 25 gp.

> ##### New Equipment Packs

### Tools

The following items belong to the Tools section of the PHB.

***Engineer's tools.*** Artisan's tools. Can also be considered tinker's tools.

***Vehicles (land).*** Chopper, hot rod, trike.

***Vehicles (air).*** Vehicles such as flying machines, hot air balloons, zeppelins, and airships.

***Vehicles (water).*** New vehicles such as submarines.

\pagebreakNum

### Mounts and Vehicles

The following items belong to the Mounts and Vehicles section of the PHB.


#### Mounts.
Mount | Cost | Speed | Carrying Capacity
---|:---:|:---:|:---:
Deathcharger | N/A | 60 ft., Fly 90 ft. | 540 lb.
Elekk | 200 gp | 40 ft. | 1,320 lb.
Felsteed | N/A | 60 ft., Fly 90 ft. | 540 lb.
Hawkstrider | 150 gp | 70 ft. | 225 lb.
Kodo | 200 gp | 40 ft. | 630 lb.
Mechanostrider | 150 gp | 70 ft. | 225 lb.
Nightsaber | 325 gp | 40 ft. | 510 lb.
Ram | 75 gp | 40 ft. | 510 lb.
Raptor | 500 gp | 60 ft. | 570 lb.
Riding Turtle | 200 gp | 40 ft., Swim 20 ft. | 1,020 lb.
Skeletal Warhorse | 500 gp | 60 ft. | 540 lb.
Worg | 325 gp | 50 ft. | 510 lb.

***Deathcharger.*** Undead horse summoned by death knights through a special ability, or through Find Greater Steed. As it is intended to act as an equivalent to the other flying mounts provided by that spell, some of the stats from a Nightmare were used.

***Elekk.*** Draenei racial mount. Elephant. 

***Felsteed.*** Special demon horse used by warlocks. Basically a nightmare, removing the ability to planar travel to drop it down to a CR 2.

***Hawkstrider.*** Blood elf racial mount. Ostrich, with a beak attack.

***Kodo.*** Tauren racial mount. Rhinoceros.

***Riding turtle.*** Technically a Dragon Turtle, but named a riding turtle to avoid confusion with the 5e creature. Prices pulled from [here](http://worldbuilderblog.me/2015/02/24/release-the-mounts/), stats as well with a couple changes: increased land speed but decreased swim speed, added the mule's ability to carry heavy burdens, and borrowed some ideas from the Giant Snapping Turtle in Tome of Annihalation.

***Raptor.*** Troll racial mount. Allosaurus, for the size. Really wanted to add in pack tactics due to its background, but would be too OP for a CR 2.

***Nightsaber.*** Uses tiger stats. Night elf racial mount.

***Ram.*** Stats of a giant goat. Used by the dwarves of Ironforge. Prices pulled from [here](http://worldbuilderblog.me/2015/02/24/release-the-mounts/).

***Mechanostrider.*** While technically a vehicle, it acts as a mount. While it doesn't require food, it does require fuel and repairs at the same cost. Used by gnomes. Used the Ostrich stats from [here](http://worldbuilderblog.me/2015/02/24/release-the-mounts/) and converted into a construct. Some bonus to long-term movement speed was needed to compensate for removal of the Medium Mount ability. Cannot wear barding?

***Skeletal Horse.*** Forsaken racial mount. Stats are normal, but alignment is changed to unaligned.

***Worg.*** Orc racial mount. Copy-pasted dire wolf.

#### Tack, Harness, and Drawn Vehicles

Item | Cost | Weight
---|---|---
Feed, Carnivore (per day) | 5 cp | 5 lb.
Fuel (per gallon) | 2 cp | 8 lb.
Sidecar | 15 gp | 50 lb.

***Feed, Carnivore.*** Consisting of various kinds of raw meat that have been jerked, smoked, or salted for preservation, a day’s worth of carnivore feed is adequate food for any Small or Medium meat-eating animal. Large creatures need 2 days worth of feed per day.

***Fuel.*** Fuel necessary for the operation of mechanical vehicles and creatures. One gallon of fuel is enough to power a Small or Medium device for 1 hour of use. Large vehicles require 2 gallons per 8 hours, Huge vehicles require 4 gallons, and so on.

***Sidecar.*** Can be added to a chopper or trike, allowing another passenger or cargo to be carried. However, this slows the vehicle's speed by 10 feet.

\pagebreakNum


#### Mechanical Vehicles (Land)

Item | Cost | Speed | Size | Carrying Capacity
---|---|---|---|:---:
Chopper | 3,000 gp | 70 ft. | Large | 395 lbs.
Hot Rod | 10,000 gp | 60 ft. | Huge | 21,70 lbs.
Trike | 250 gp | 50 ft. | Medium | 290 lbs.

Mechanical vehicles are self-driven vehicles. Essentially they are both cart and camel rolled into one. They require fuel to function, require semi-regular maintenance, and each can only be operated by someone who possesses both a proficiency in vehicles and the unique key needed to start them up.

Unlike normal vehicles, a mechanical vehicle can be pushed to a "gallop" like a mount at the cost of twice the normal fuel consumption. This can be done for short periods of time, up to an hour, before the engine overheats and needs maintenance (a DC 12 Intelligence or tinker's tool check).

[Notes on carrying capacity: Measured in "horsepower" (the number of effective horses pulling them times the carrying capacity of a horse) then subtract the weight of the vehicle. Chopper has 2 horsepower, hot rod has 8 horsepower, trike has 1. Chopper's weight is based on the average chopper weight, likewise for hot rod, and a trike is treated as a dirt bike.]

***Chopper.*** Aka [Mechano-Hod](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Mechano-Hog) or [Mekgineer's Chopper](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Mekgineer%27s_Chopper). Medium size, 685 lb. Can carry 1 passenger--the driver. Can fit anywhere a horse could, and can carry saddlebags.

***Hot Rod.*** ([Hot Rod](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Hot_rod)) Goblin "stylish" self-driven land vehicle. Weighs 2150 lbs., can carry the driver and up to three passengers. Comes either covered or as a "convertible." 

***Trike.*** Goblin racial 'mount.' Weighs 250 lb., can only carry one passenger. Can fit anywhere a mule could, and can carry saddlebags.


#### Mechanical Vehicles (Air)

Item | Cost | Speed
---|---|---
Gyrocopter | 10,000 gp | 90 ft./round
Zeppelin | 30,000 gp | 3 mph

Mechanical air vehicles follow most of the same rules as mechanical land vehicles. 

***Gyrocopter.*** [Link](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Gyrocopter). Primarily a gnomish invention, a gyrocopter is a Large-sized personal air transport. Having to constantly spin its propellors to keep itself aloft causes the gyrocopter to require far more fuel to keep themselves from succumbing to the forces of gravity. It burns through a gallon of fuel every ten minutes instead of every hour. It can only carry 300 pounds worth of passengers and gear.

***Zeppelin.*** [Link](https://wow.gamepedia.com/Zeppelin). Created by the goblins, zeppelins use a lighter-than-air design combined with a propellor engine to provide a smooth, long distance ride through the air much like a ship through water. They can carry far less than a waterborne ship of equivalent size though, due to buoyancy requirements.

